Here's how to implement all three:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button (in `EditProductPage.xaml`)

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

In your ViewModel:

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Back()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

### 2. Guard the hardware/swipe back too (in `AppShell.xaml.cs`)

The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the shell back button, but **hardware back** and **swipe gestures** bypass it. Guard those with `OnNavigating`:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **`GetDeferral()`** is required because the confirmation is async â€” without it you'd have a race condition.
- **`args.Cancel()`** prevents navigation when the user picks "Stay".
- **`args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop`** ensures the guard only fires on back navigation, not forward pushes.
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the default back arrow tap, so set your own `GoToAsync("..")` in the command after confirmation.
